================================================
FILE: auto-update-rank.sql
================================================
-- Auto-update user rank based on XP changes
-- This function will automatically update the rank column when XP changes

-- Create function to calculate rank from XP
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION calculate_rank_from_xp(xp_amount INTEGER)
RETURNS TEXT AS $$
BEGIN
    RETURN CASE
        WHEN xp_amount >= 8000 THEN 'CFO'
        WHEN xp_amount >= 4000 THEN 'Master'
        WHEN xp_amount >= 2000 THEN 'Mogul'
        WHEN xp_amount >= 1000 THEN 'Wizard'
        WHEN xp_amount >= 500 THEN 'Clerk'
        ELSE 'Novice'
    END;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- Create function to update rank when XP changes
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION update_user_rank()
RETURNS TRIGGER AS $$
BEGIN
    -- Only update if XP has changed
    IF OLD.xp IS DISTINCT FROM NEW.xp THEN
        NEW.rank = calculate_rank_from_xp(NEW.xp);
        
        -- Log the level up if it happened
        IF OLD.rank IS DISTINCT FROM NEW.rank THEN
            RAISE NOTICE 'User % leveled up from % to % (XP: % -> %)', 
                NEW.id, OLD.rank, NEW.rank, OLD.xp, NEW.xp;
        END IF;
    END IF;
    
    RETURN NEW;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- Create trigger to automatically update rank
DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS trigger_update_user_rank ON public.users;
CREATE TRIGGER trigger_update_user_rank
    BEFORE UPDATE ON public.users
    FOR EACH ROW
    EXECUTE FUNCTION update_user_rank();

-- Update existing users' ranks to match their current XP
UPDATE public.users 
SET rank = calculate_rank_from_xp(xp)
WHERE rank IS NULL OR rank != calculate_rank_from_xp(xp);

-- Test the function
SELECT 
    id, 
    name, 
    xp, 
    rank, 
    calculate_rank_from_xp(xp) as calculated_rank
FROM public.users 
LIMIT 5;

FILE: database-hearts-migration.sql
================================================
-- Heart System Database Migration
-- Run this in your Supabase SQL editor

-- 1. Add heart columns to users table
ALTER TABLE users 
ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS hearts INTEGER DEFAULT 5,
ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS max_hearts INTEGER DEFAULT 5,
ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS last_heart_loss TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE,
ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS last_heart_replenish TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE;

-- 2. Create heart_history table
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS heart_history (
  id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
  user_id UUID REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  hearts_change INTEGER NOT NULL,
  reason TEXT NOT NULL,
  previous_hearts INTEGER NOT NULL,
  new_hearts INTEGER NOT NULL,
  timestamp TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW()
);

-- 3. Create indexes for performance
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_heart_history_user_id ON heart_history(user_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_heart_history_timestamp ON heart_history(timestamp);

-- 4. Update existing users to have default heart values
UPDATE users 
SET 
  hearts = 5,
  max_hearts = 5,
  last_heart_replenish = NOW()
WHERE hearts IS NULL OR max_hearts IS NULL;

-- 5. Create a function to automatically replenish hearts
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION check_and_replenish_hearts()
RETURNS void AS $$
BEGIN
  UPDATE users 
  SET 
    hearts = LEAST(max_hearts, hearts + 1),
    last_heart_replenish = NOW()
  WHERE 
    hearts < max_hearts 
    AND last_heart_loss IS NOT NULL
    AND EXTRACT(EPOCH FROM (NOW() - last_heart_loss)) >= 43200; -- 12 hours in seconds
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- 6. Create a trigger to log heart changes
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION log_heart_change()
RETURNS TRIGGER AS $$
BEGIN
  IF OLD.hearts IS DISTINCT FROM NEW.hearts THEN
    INSERT INTO heart_history (
      user_id, 
      hearts_change, 
      reason, 
      previous_hearts, 
      new_hearts, 
      timestamp
    ) VALUES (
      NEW.id,
      NEW.hearts - OLD.hearts,
      CASE 
        WHEN NEW.hearts > OLD.hearts THEN 'replenish'
        ELSE 'wrong_answer'
      END,
      OLD.hearts,
      NEW.hearts,
      NOW()
    );
  END IF;
  RETURN NEW;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- 7. Create trigger on users table
DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS trigger_log_heart_change ON users;
CREATE TRIGGER trigger_log_heart_change
  AFTER UPDATE ON users
  FOR EACH ROW
  EXECUTE FUNCTION log_heart_change();

-- 8. Set up a cron job to replenish hearts every hour (optional)
-- Note: This requires pg_cron extension to be enabled
-- SELECT cron.schedule('replenish-hearts', '0 * * * *', 'SELECT check_and_replenish_hearts();');

-- Success message
SELECT 'Heart system migration completed successfully!' as status;



================================================
FILE: database-setup.sql
================================================
-- Database setup script for FinancePal app
-- WARNING: This schema is for context only and is not meant to be run.
-- Table order and constraints may not be valid for execution.

CREATE TABLE public.categories (
  id bigint GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY NOT NULL,
  name character varying NOT NULL,
  emoji character varying,
  description text,
  CONSTRAINT categories_pkey PRIMARY KEY (id)
);
CREATE TABLE public.chapters (
  id bigint GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY NOT NULL,
  categoryID bigint NOT NULL,
  name character varying,
  order bigint,
  description character varying,
  CONSTRAINT chapters_pkey PRIMARY KEY (id),
  CONSTRAINT chapters_categoryID_fkey FOREIGN KEY (categoryID) REFERENCES public.categories(id)
);
CREATE TABLE public.lessons (
  id bigint GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY NOT NULL,
  chapterID bigint NOT NULL,
  name character varying,
  orderNo bigint,
  CONSTRAINT lessons_pkey PRIMARY KEY (id),
  CONSTRAINT lessons_chapterID_fkey FOREIGN KEY (chapterID) REFERENCES public.chapters(id)
);
CREATE TABLE public.stories (
  id bigint GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY NOT NULL,
  lessonID bigint NOT NULL,
  title character varying,
  description character varying,
  difficulty_level character varying DEFAULT 'beginner'::character varying,
  xp_reward integer DEFAULT 10,
  estimated_duration integer DEFAULT 5,
  CONSTRAINT stories_pkey PRIMARY KEY (id),
  CONSTRAINT stories_lessonID_fkey FOREIGN KEY (lessonID) REFERENCES public.lessons(id)
);
CREATE TABLE public.story_answers (
  id bigint GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY NOT NULL,
  questionID bigint NOT NULL,
  answer character varying,
  correct boolean,
  CONSTRAINT story_answers_pkey PRIMARY KEY (id),
  CONSTRAINT story_answers_questionID_fkey FOREIGN KEY (questionID) REFERENCES public.story_questions(id)
);
CREATE TABLE public.story_pages (
  id bigint GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY NOT NULL,
  story_id bigint NOT NULL,
  page_number bigint,
  content character varying,
  CONSTRAINT story_pages_pkey PRIMARY KEY (id),
  CONSTRAINT story_pages_story_id_fkey FOREIGN KEY (story_id) REFERENCES public.stories(id)
);
CREATE TABLE public.story_questions (
  id bigint GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY NOT NULL,
  story bigint NOT NULL,
  question character varying,
  type character varying,
  xp_reward integer DEFAULT 5,
  difficulty integer DEFAULT 1,
  CONSTRAINT story_questions_pkey PRIMARY KEY (id),
  CONSTRAINT story_questions_story_fkey FOREIGN KEY (story) REFERENCES public.stories(id)
);
CREATE TABLE public.user_achievements (
  id uuid NOT NULL DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),
  user_id uuid,
  achievement_type character varying NOT NULL,
  earned_at timestamp with time zone DEFAULT now(),
  xp_reward integer DEFAULT 0,
  CONSTRAINT user_achievements_pkey PRIMARY KEY (id),
  CONSTRAINT user_achievements_user_id_fkey FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES public.users(id)
);
CREATE TABLE public.user_learning_progress (
  id uuid NOT NULL DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),
  user_id uuid NOT NULL,
  category_id bigint NOT NULL,
  current_chapter_id bigint,
  current_course_index integer DEFAULT 0,
  is_active boolean DEFAULT false,
  started_at timestamp with time zone DEFAULT now(),
  updated_at timestamp with time zone DEFAULT now(),
  CONSTRAINT user_learning_progress_pkey PRIMARY KEY (id),
  CONSTRAINT user_learning_progress_current_chapter_id_fkey FOREIGN KEY (current_chapter_id) REFERENCES public.chapters(id),
  CONSTRAINT user_learning_progress_category_id_fkey FOREIGN KEY (category_id) REFERENCES public.categories(id),
  CONSTRAINT user_learning_progress_user_id_fkey FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES public.users(id)
);
CREATE TABLE public.user_progress (
  id uuid NOT NULL DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),
  user_id uuid,
  lesson_id integer,
  story_id integer,
  completed boolean DEFAULT false,
  completed_at timestamp with time zone,
  current_page integer DEFAULT 0,
  quiz_score integer,
  quiz_completed boolean DEFAULT false,
  quiz_completed_at timestamp with time zone,
  xp_earned integer DEFAULT 0,
  created_at timestamp with time zone DEFAULT now(),
  updated_at timestamp with time zone DEFAULT now(),
  CONSTRAINT user_progress_pkey PRIMARY KEY (id),
  CONSTRAINT user_progress_story_id_fkey FOREIGN KEY (story_id) REFERENCES public.stories(id),
  CONSTRAINT user_progress_lesson_id_fkey FOREIGN KEY (lesson_id) REFERENCES public.lessons(id)
);
CREATE TABLE public.user_streaks (
  id uuid NOT NULL DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),
  user_id uuid,
  date date NOT NULL,
  activity_type character varying NOT NULL,
  CONSTRAINT user_streaks_pkey PRIMARY KEY (id),
  CONSTRAINT user_streaks_user_id_fkey FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES public.users(id)
);
CREATE TABLE public.users (
  id uuid NOT NULL DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),
  email character varying NOT NULL UNIQUE,
  created_at timestamp with time zone DEFAULT now(),
  updated_at timestamp with time zone DEFAULT now(),
  name character varying,
  avatar character varying,
  xp integer DEFAULT 0,
  streak integer DEFAULT 0,
  rank character varying DEFAULT 'Novice'::character varying,
  financial_literacy_level character varying DEFAULT 'Novice'::character varying,
  onboarding_completed boolean DEFAULT false,
  theme_preference character varying DEFAULT 'system'::character varying,
  auth_user_id uuid,
  CONSTRAINT users_pkey PRIMARY KEY (id),
  CONSTRAINT users_auth_user_id_fkey FOREIGN KEY (auth_user_id) REFERENCES auth.users(id)
);

FILE: fix-goal-members-rls-policies.sql
================================================
-- Fix RLS Policies for goal_members table
-- Run this in your Supabase SQL Editor

-- 1. Drop existing policies that don't work correctly
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Users can view members of goals they're part of" ON goal_members;
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Goal owners can add/remove members" ON goal_members;

-- 2. Create new policies that work with public.users table
-- Policy: Users can view members of goals they're part of
CREATE POLICY "Users can view members of goals they're part of" ON goal_members
  FOR SELECT USING (
    EXISTS (
      SELECT 1 FROM goal_members gm 
      JOIN users u ON gm.user_id = u.id
      WHERE gm.goal_id = goal_members.goal_id 
      AND u.auth_user_id = auth.uid()
    )
  );

-- Policy: Only goal owners can add/remove members
CREATE POLICY "Goal owners can add/remove members" ON goal_members
  FOR ALL USING (
    EXISTS (
      SELECT 1 FROM goal_members gm 
      JOIN users u ON gm.user_id = u.id
      WHERE gm.goal_id = goal_members.goal_id 
      AND u.auth_user_id = auth.uid() 
      AND gm.role = 'owner'
    )
  );

-- 3. Also fix the goal_invitations policies
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Goal owners can send invitations" ON goal_invitations;

CREATE POLICY "Goal owners can send invitations" ON goal_invitations
  FOR INSERT WITH CHECK (
    EXISTS (
      SELECT 1 FROM goal_members gm 
      JOIN users u ON gm.user_id = u.id
      WHERE gm.goal_id = goal_invitations.goal_id 
      AND u.auth_user_id = auth.uid() 
      AND gm.role = 'owner'
    )
  );

-- 4. Fix goal_contributions policies
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Goal members can add contributions" ON goal_contributions;

CREATE POLICY "Goal members can add contributions" ON goal_contributions
  FOR INSERT WITH CHECK (
    EXISTS (
      SELECT 1 FROM goal_members gm 
      JOIN users u ON gm.user_id = u.id
      WHERE gm.goal_id = goal_contributions.goal_id 
      AND u.auth_user_id = auth.uid() 
      AND gm.role IN ('owner', 'contributor')
    )
  );

-- 5. Add a policy to prevent non-owners from modifying goal_members
-- This ensures that only owners can INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE members
CREATE POLICY "Only owners can modify goal members" ON goal_members
  FOR INSERT WITH CHECK (
    EXISTS (
      SELECT 1 FROM goal_members gm 
      JOIN users u ON gm.user_id = u.id
      WHERE gm.goal_id = goal_members.goal_id 
      AND u.auth_user_id = auth.uid() 
      AND gm.role = 'owner'
    )
  );

CREATE POLICY "Only owners can modify goal members" ON goal_members
  FOR UPDATE USING (
    EXISTS (
      SELECT 1 FROM goal_members gm 
      JOIN users u ON gm.user_id = u.id
      WHERE gm.goal_id = goal_members.goal_id 
      AND u.auth_user_id = auth.uid() 
      AND gm.role = 'owner'
    )
  );

CREATE POLICY "Only owners can modify goal members" ON goal_members
  FOR DELETE USING (
    EXISTS (
      SELECT 1 FROM goal_members gm 
      JOIN users u ON gm.user_id = u.id
      WHERE gm.goal_id = goal_members.goal_id 
      AND u.auth_user_id = auth.uid() 
      AND gm.role = 'owner'
    )
  );

-- 6. Grant necessary permissions
GRANT SELECT ON goal_members TO authenticated;
GRANT INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON goal_members TO authenticated;

-- 7. Add comments for documentation
COMMENT ON POLICY "Users can view members of goals they're part of" ON goal_members IS 'Allows users to view members of goals they are part of';
COMMENT ON POLICY "Goal owners can add/remove members" ON goal_members IS 'Allows goal owners to manage all aspects of goal members';
COMMENT ON POLICY "Only owners can modify goal members" ON goal_members IS 'Restricts member modification to only goal owners';

FILE: fix-goals-rls-and-income.sql
================================================
-- Fix Goals Table RLS Policies and Add User Income Tracking
-- Run this in your Supabase SQL Editor

-- 1. First, let's check if the goals table exists and has the right structure
DO $$ 
BEGIN
    -- Create goals table if it doesn't exist
    IF NOT EXISTS (SELECT FROM information_schema.tables WHERE table_name = 'goals') THEN
        CREATE TABLE goals (
            id UUID DEFAULT gen_random_uuid() PRIMARY KEY,
            user_id UUID REFERENCES auth.users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
            title TEXT NOT NULL,
            description TEXT,
            target_amount DECIMAL(12,2) NOT NULL,
            current_amount DECIMAL(12,2) DEFAULT 0,
            deadline DATE NOT NULL,
            category TEXT NOT NULL,
            color TEXT DEFAULT '#A2E57B',
            completed BOOLEAN DEFAULT FALSE,
            created_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW(),
            updated_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW()
        );
        
        -- Create indexes for better performance
        CREATE INDEX idx_goals_user_id ON goals(user_id);
        CREATE INDEX idx_goals_completed ON goals(completed);
        CREATE INDEX idx_goals_deadline ON goals(deadline);
        
        -- Create function to update updated_at timestamp
        CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION update_updated_at_column()
        RETURNS TRIGGER AS $func$
        BEGIN
            NEW.updated_at = NOW();
            RETURN NEW;
        END;
        $func$ language 'plpgsql';
        
        -- Create trigger to automatically update updated_at
        CREATE TRIGGER update_goals_updated_at 
            BEFORE UPDATE ON goals 
            FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE FUNCTION update_updated_at_column();
            
        RAISE NOTICE 'Goals table created successfully';
    ELSE
        RAISE NOTICE 'Goals table already exists';
    END IF;
END $$;

-- 2. Enable Row Level Security on goals table
ALTER TABLE goals ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;

-- 3. Drop existing policies if they exist (to avoid conflicts)
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Users can view their own goals" ON goals;
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Users can insert their own goals" ON goals;
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Users can update their own goals" ON goals;
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Users can delete their own goals" ON goals;

-- 4. Create proper RLS policies
CREATE POLICY "Users can view their own goals" ON goals
    FOR SELECT USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

CREATE POLICY "Users can insert their own goals" ON goals
    FOR INSERT WITH CHECK (auth.uid() = user_id);

CREATE POLICY "Users can update their own goals" ON goals
    FOR UPDATE USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

CREATE POLICY "Users can delete their own goals" ON goals
    FOR DELETE USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- 5. Add user income tracking to users table
DO $$ 
BEGIN
    -- Add income fields to users table if they don't exist
    IF NOT EXISTS (SELECT FROM information_schema.columns WHERE table_name = 'users' AND column_name = 'monthly_income') THEN
        ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN monthly_income DECIMAL(12,2);
        RAISE NOTICE 'Added monthly_income column to users table';
    ELSE
        RAISE NOTICE 'monthly_income column already exists in users table';
    END IF;
    
    IF NOT EXISTS (SELECT FROM information_schema.columns WHERE table_name = 'users' AND column_name = 'income_frequency') THEN
        ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN income_frequency TEXT DEFAULT 'monthly' CHECK (income_frequency IN ('weekly', 'biweekly', 'monthly', 'yearly'));
        RAISE NOTICE 'Added income_frequency column to users table';
    ELSE
        RAISE NOTICE 'income_frequency column already exists in users table';
    END IF;
    
    IF NOT EXISTS (SELECT FROM information_schema.columns WHERE table_name = 'users' AND column_name = 'financial_goals_enabled') THEN
        ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN financial_goals_enabled BOOLEAN DEFAULT TRUE;
        RAISE NOTICE 'Added financial_goals_enabled column to users table';
    ELSE
        RAISE NOTICE 'financial_goals_enabled column already exists in users table';
    END IF;
END $$;

-- 6. Create a function to calculate goal progress percentage
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION calculate_goal_progress(goal_id UUID)
RETURNS DECIMAL(5,2) AS $$
DECLARE
    progress DECIMAL(5,2);
BEGIN
    SELECT 
        CASE 
            WHEN target_amount = 0 THEN 0
            ELSE ROUND((current_amount / target_amount) * 100, 2)
        END
    INTO progress
    FROM goals 
    WHERE id = goal_id;
    
    RETURN COALESCE(progress, 0);
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- 7. Create a function to get user's financial summary
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION get_user_financial_summary(user_uuid UUID)
RETURNS TABLE(
    total_goals INTEGER,
    completed_goals INTEGER,
    active_goals INTEGER,
    total_target_amount DECIMAL(12,2),
    total_current_amount DECIMAL(12,2),
    overall_progress DECIMAL(5,2),
    monthly_income DECIMAL(12,2),
    income_frequency TEXT
) AS $$
BEGIN
    RETURN QUERY
    SELECT 
        COUNT(*)::INTEGER as total_goals,
        COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE completed = true)::INTEGER as completed_goals,
        COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE completed = false)::INTEGER as active_goals,
        COALESCE(SUM(target_amount), 0) as total_target_amount,
        COALESCE(SUM(current_amount), 0) as total_current_amount,
        CASE 
            WHEN SUM(target_amount) = 0 THEN 0
            ELSE ROUND((SUM(current_amount) / SUM(target_amount)) * 100, 2)
        END as overall_progress,
        u.monthly_income,
        u.income_frequency
    FROM goals g
    LEFT JOIN users u ON g.user_id = u.id
    WHERE g.user_id = user_uuid
    GROUP BY u.monthly_income, u.income_frequency;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- 8. Create a view for goal insights
CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW goal_insights AS
SELECT 
    g.id,
    g.user_id,
    g.title,
    g.category,
    g.target_amount,
    g.current_amount,
    g.deadline,
    g.completed,
    g.created_at,
    g.updated_at,
    calculate_goal_progress(g.id) as progress_percentage,
    CASE 
        WHEN g.deadline < CURRENT_DATE THEN 'overdue'
        WHEN g.deadline = CURRENT_DATE THEN 'due_today'
        WHEN g.deadline <= CURRENT_DATE + INTERVAL '7 days' THEN 'due_soon'
        ELSE 'on_track'
    END as deadline_status,
    g.deadline - CURRENT_DATE as days_remaining
FROM goals g;

-- 9. Grant necessary permissions
GRANT SELECT ON goal_insights TO authenticated;
GRANT EXECUTE ON FUNCTION calculate_goal_progress(UUID) TO authenticated;
GRANT EXECUTE ON FUNCTION get_user_financial_summary(UUID) TO authenticated;

-- 10. Test the setup by inserting a sample goal (optional)
-- Uncomment the lines below to test if everything works
/*
INSERT INTO goals (user_id, title, target_amount, deadline, category, color)
VALUES (
    (SELECT id FROM auth.users LIMIT 1),
    'Test Emergency Fund',
    5000.00,
    CURRENT_DATE + INTERVAL '6 months',
    'Savings',
    '#A2E57B'
);
*/

-- Script completed successfully!
SELECT 'Goals table RLS policies and income tracking setup completed successfully!' as status;

FILE: fix-rls-policies.sql

-- Fix RLS policies for leaderboard functionality
-- This script will allow users to see other users' XP for leaderboard purposes

-- First, let's see what RLS policies currently exist
SELECT schemaname, tablename, policyname, permissive, roles, cmd, qual, with_check 
FROM pg_policies 
WHERE tablename = 'users';

-- Drop existing restrictive policies (if any)
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Users can only see their own data" ON public.users;
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Users can only update their own data" ON public.users;
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Users can only insert their own data" ON public.users;

-- Create new policies that allow leaderboard functionality

-- Policy 1: Allow users to read their own data (for profile, etc.)
CREATE POLICY "Users can read own data" ON public.users
    FOR SELECT
    USING (auth.uid() = id);

-- Policy 2: Allow users to read other users' data for leaderboard (only name and xp)
CREATE POLICY "Users can read leaderboard data" ON public.users
    FOR SELECT
    USING (true); -- Allow reading all users for leaderboard

-- Policy 3: Allow users to update their own data
CREATE POLICY "Users can update own data" ON public.users
    FOR UPDATE
    USING (auth.uid() = id);

-- Policy 4: Allow users to insert their own data
CREATE POLICY "Users can insert own data" ON public.users
    FOR INSERT
    WITH CHECK (auth.uid() = id);

-- Enable RLS if not already enabled
ALTER TABLE public.users ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;

-- Test the policies
-- This should now return all users for leaderboard purposes
-- SELECT id, name, xp FROM public.users ORDER BY xp DESC;

FILE: fix-user-progress-rls.sql
================================================
-- Fix RLS policies for user_progress table to allow friends to see weekly XP
-- This script will allow users to see their friends' weekly progress for leaderboard purposes

-- First, let's see what RLS policies currently exist for user_progress
SELECT schemaname, tablename, policyname, permissive, roles, cmd, qual, with_check 
FROM pg_policies 
WHERE tablename = 'user_progress';

-- Drop existing restrictive policies (if any)
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Users can only see their own progress" ON public.user_progress;
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Users can only update their own progress" ON public.user_progress;
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Users can only insert their own progress" ON public.user_progress;

-- Create new policies that allow leaderboard functionality

-- Policy 1: Allow users to read their own progress data
CREATE POLICY "Users can read own progress" ON public.user_progress
    FOR SELECT
    USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- Policy 2: Allow users to read friends' progress data for weekly leaderboard
-- This policy allows reading progress data for users who are friends
CREATE POLICY "Users can read friends progress for leaderboard" ON public.user_progress
    FOR SELECT
    USING (
        EXISTS (
            SELECT 1 FROM public.friends 
            WHERE (user_id = auth.uid() AND friend_id = user_progress.user_id AND status = 'accepted')
               OR (friend_id = auth.uid() AND user_id = user_progress.user_id AND status = 'accepted')
        )
    );

-- Policy 3: Allow users to update their own progress
CREATE POLICY "Users can update own progress" ON public.user_progress
    FOR UPDATE
    USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- Policy 4: Allow users to insert their own progress
CREATE POLICY "Users can insert own progress" ON public.user_progress
    FOR INSERT
    WITH CHECK (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- Policy 5: Allow users to delete their own progress
CREATE POLICY "Users can delete own progress" ON public.user_progress
    FOR DELETE
    USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- Enable RLS if not already enabled
ALTER TABLE public.user_progress ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;

-- Test the policies
-- This should now return progress data for friends
-- SELECT up.user_id, up.xp_earned, up.completed_at 
-- FROM public.user_progress up
-- JOIN public.friends f ON (f.user_id = auth.uid() AND f.friend_id = up.user_id AND f.status = 'accepted')
--    OR (f.friend_id = auth.uid() AND f.user_id = up.user_id AND f.status = 'accepted')
-- WHERE up.completed = true AND up.xp_earned > 0;

FILE: HEART_SYSTEM_README.md
================================================
# â¤ï¸ Heart System Implementation

This document explains how the heart system works in the FinancePal app, where users lose hearts for wrong answers and regain them after 12 hours.

## ðŸŽ¯ Overview

The heart system is designed to:
- **Limit learning attempts** by deducting hearts for wrong answers
- **Encourage spaced repetition** by replenishing hearts after 12 hours
- **Track user progress** with detailed heart history
- **Provide visual feedback** showing current heart status and replenishment time

## ðŸ—ï¸ Architecture

### **Server-Side Heart Management** âš ï¸ **CRITICAL**

The heart system is **primarily server-side** for security and reliability:

#### **Why Server-Side?**
- **ðŸ”’ Anti-Cheat Protection**: Prevents client-side manipulation
- **âš¡ Reliable Timing**: Server ensures accurate 12-hour replenishment
- **ðŸŒ Data Consistency**: Single source of truth across all devices
- **ðŸ›¡ï¸ Security**: Heart counts cannot be tampered with

#### **Server Components**
- **Supabase Edge Functions**: Server-side heart management and validation
- **Supabase Cron Jobs**: Automatic heart replenishment every 6 hours
- **Database Triggers**: Automatic logging of all heart changes
- **Real-time Updates**: Live heart status via Supabase subscriptions

### Database Schema

#### Users Table
- `hearts` (INTEGER): Current hearts (0-5)
- `max_hearts` (INTEGER): Maximum hearts (default: 5)
- `last_heart_loss` (TIMESTAMP): When hearts were last lost
- `last_heart_replenish` (TIMESTAMP): When hearts were last replenished

#### Heart History Table
- `user_id` (UUID): Reference to user
- `hearts_change` (INTEGER): Positive for gain, negative for loss
- `reason` (TEXT): "wrong_answer", "replenish", "bonus"
- `previous_hearts` (INTEGER): Hearts before change
- `new_hearts` (INTEGER): Hearts after change
- `timestamp` (TIMESTAMP): When change occurred

### Frontend Components

#### HeartDisplay Component
- **Location**: `components/HeartDisplay.tsx`
- **Features**:
  - Visual heart indicators (filled/empty)
  - Replenishment timer countdown
  - Ready indicator when hearts can be replenished
  - Multiple sizes (small, medium, large)
  - Optional timer display

#### Heart Management Hook
- **Location**: `hooks/useHeartReplenishment.ts`
- **Features**:
  - Automatic heart replenishment checks
  - Manual replenishment triggers
  - Background monitoring

## ðŸš€ Setup Instructions

### 1. **Database Migration** (Required First)

Run the SQL migration in your Supabase SQL editor:

```sql
-- Run database-hearts-migration.sql
```

Or manually execute:

```sql
-- Add heart columns to users table
ALTER TABLE users 
ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS hearts INTEGER DEFAULT 5,
ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS max_hearts INTEGER DEFAULT 5,
ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS last_heart_loss TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE,
ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS last_heart_replenish TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE;

-- Create heart_history table
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS heart_history (
  id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
  user_id UUID REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  hearts_change INTEGER NOT NULL,
  reason TEXT NOT NULL,
  previous_hearts INTEGER NOT NULL,
  new_hearts INTEGER NOT NULL,
  timestamp TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW()
);

-- Create indexes
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_heart_history_user_id ON heart_history(user_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_heart_history_timestamp ON heart_history(timestamp);
```

### 2. **Supabase Edge Functions & Cron Jobs Setup** (Server-Side Hearts)

The heart system uses **Supabase Edge Functions** and **cron jobs** for automatic server-side replenishment:

#### **Edge Function Setup**
```bash
# Deploy the heart management function
supabase functions deploy heart-management

# Deploy the cron function
supabase functions deploy cron-heart-replenishment
```

#### **Cron Job Configuration**
```toml
# In supabase/config.toml
[[cron.jobs]]
name = "heart-replenishment"
schedule = "0 */6 * * *"  # Every 6 hours
function = "cron-heart-replenishment"
```

**âš ï¸ Important**: This ensures hearts are replenished server-side every 6 hours, not client-side!

### 3. **Update Existing Users**

Run the migration script:

```bash
node scripts/update-users-hearts.js
```

### 4. **Supabase Edge Functions**

The heart system uses these Supabase Edge Functions:

- `heart-management`: Main function for all heart operations
  - `get_heart_status`: Get current heart status
  - `deduct_heart`: Remove heart for wrong answer
  - `replenish_hearts`: Add heart after 12 hours
  - `check_all_replenishment`: Bulk replenishment
- `cron-heart-replenishment`: Automated cron job for heart replenishment

## ðŸ’¡ Usage Examples

### Displaying Hearts in UI

```tsx
import { HeartDisplay } from '../components/HeartDisplay';

// Basic usage
<HeartDisplay />

// With custom size and no timer
<HeartDisplay size="small" showTimer={false} />

// With click handler
<HeartDisplay onHeartPress={() => router.push('/profile')} />
```

### Deducting Hearts for Wrong Answers

```tsx
import { supabase } from '../services/supabase';

const handleWrongAnswer = async () => {
  try {
    const { data, error } = await supabase.functions.invoke('heart-management', {
      body: { 
        action: 'deduct_heart', 
        userId: user.id, 
        reason: 'wrong_answer',
        lessonId: currentLesson.id 
      }
    });

    if (error) throw error;
    // Show feedback to user
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error deducting heart:', error);
  }
};
```

### Checking Heart Status

```tsx
import { supabase } from '../services/supabase';

const { data: heartStatus, error } = await supabase.functions.invoke('heart-management', {
  body: { action: 'get_heart_status', userId: user.id }
});

if (heartStatus) {
  console.log('Current hearts:', heartStatus.currentHearts);
  console.log('Time until replenish:', heartStatus.timeUntilReplenish);
  console.log('Can replenish:', heartStatus.shouldReplenish);
}
```

## â° Heart Replenishment Logic

### Automatic Replenishment
- **Frequency**: Every 6 hours (via Supabase cron job)
- **Condition**: 12 hours since last heart loss
- **Amount**: 1 heart per replenishment cycle
- **Maximum**: Cannot exceed `max_hearts` (default: 5)

### Manual Replenishment
- **Trigger**: User action or app refresh
- **Validation**: Checks 12-hour requirement
- **Response**: Immediate feedback on success/failure

## ðŸŽ¨ UI Features

### Heart Display States
1. **Filled Hearts** (â¤ï¸): Available hearts
2. **Empty Hearts** (ðŸ¤): Lost hearts
3. **Replenishing Heart** (ðŸ”„): Next heart to be restored
4. **Timer Display**: Countdown to next replenishment
5. **Ready Indicator**: Green checkmark when replenishment is available

### Visual Feedback
- **Colors**: Red for hearts, green for replenishment
- **Animations**: Smooth transitions and indicators
- **Responsive**: Different sizes for different contexts
- **Accessible**: Clear visual hierarchy and contrast

## ðŸ”§ Configuration

### Heart Limits
- **Default Max Hearts**: 5
- **Replenishment Time**: 12 hours
- **Check Frequency**: Every 6 hours (server-side)

### Customization
You can modify these values in the Supabase Edge Functions:

```typescript
// In supabase/functions/heart-management/index.ts
const MAX_HEARTS = 5;
const HEART_REPLENISH_HOURS = 12;
```

## ðŸ“± Integration Points

### Home Screen
- Hearts displayed in stats row
- Clickable to navigate to profile

### Profile Screen
- Large heart display with timer
- Heart history and management

### Lessons/Quizzes
- Heart deduction on wrong answers
- Heart status display during learning

### Leaderboard
- Hearts as part of user stats
- Visual indicators for heart status

## ðŸš¨ Error Handling

### Common Scenarios
1. **No Hearts Remaining**: User cannot continue learning
2. **Replenishment Too Early**: Timer shows remaining time
3. **Database Errors**: Graceful fallback and user feedback
4. **Network Issues**: Offline support and retry logic

### User Experience
- Clear error messages
- Visual indicators for problems
- Helpful guidance on next steps
- Graceful degradation when possible

// metro.config.js
const { getDefaultConfig } = require('@expo/metro-config');

const defaultConfig = getDefaultConfig(__dirname);

module.exports = {
  ...defaultConfig,
  server: {
    ...defaultConfig.server,
    enhanceMiddleware: (middleware) => {
      return (req, res, next) => {
        // Set custom timeout (in milliseconds)
        req.setTimeout(30000); // 30 seconds
        res.setTimeout(30000); // 30 seconds

        return middleware(req, res, next);
      };
    }
  },
  watcher: {
    ...defaultConfig.watcher,
    unstable_lazySha1: true, // Enable lazy SHA1 computation for better performance
  }
};

FILE: multi-user-goals-schema.sql
================================================
-- Multi-Contributor Goals Database Schema
-- Run this in your Supabase SQL editor

-- 1. Goal Members Table (who can contribute to each goal)
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS goal_members (
  id UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),
  goal_id UUID REFERENCES goals(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  user_id UUID REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  role TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'contributor' CHECK (role IN ('owner', 'contributor', 'viewer')),
  joined_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW(),
  UNIQUE(goal_id, user_id)
);

-- 2. Goal Invitations Table (pending invitations)
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS goal_invitations (
  id UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),
  goal_id UUID REFERENCES goals(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  invited_user_id UUID REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  invited_by UUID REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  status TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'pending' CHECK (status IN ('pending', 'accepted', 'declined')),
  invited_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW(),
  responded_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE,
  UNIQUE(goal_id, invited_user_id)
);

-- 3. Goal Contributions Table (track who contributed what)
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS goal_contributions (
  id UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),
  goal_id UUID REFERENCES goals(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  user_id UUID REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  amount DECIMAL(10,2) NOT NULL CHECK (amount > 0),
  contributed_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW(),
  note TEXT,
  created_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW()
);

-- 4. Add indexes for better performance
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_goal_members_goal_id ON goal_members(goal_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_goal_members_user_id ON goal_members(user_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_goal_invitations_goal_id ON goal_invitations(goal_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_goal_invitations_invited_user_id ON goal_invitations(invited_user_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_goal_contributions_goal_id ON goal_contributions(goal_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_goal_contributions_user_id ON goal_contributions(user_id);

-- 5. Set up Row Level Security (RLS)
ALTER TABLE goal_members ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
ALTER TABLE goal_invitations ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
ALTER TABLE goal_contributions ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;

-- 6. RLS Policies for goal_members
CREATE POLICY "Users can view members of goals they're part of" ON goal_members
  FOR SELECT USING (
    EXISTS (
      SELECT 1 FROM goal_members gm 
      WHERE gm.goal_id = goal_members.goal_id 
      AND gm.user_id = auth.uid()
    )
  );

CREATE POLICY "Goal owners can add/remove members" ON goal_members
  FOR ALL USING (
    EXISTS (
      SELECT 1 FROM goal_members gm 
      WHERE gm.goal_id = goal_members.goal_id 
      AND gm.user_id = auth.uid() 
      AND gm.role = 'owner'
    )
  );

-- 7. RLS Policies for goal_invitations
CREATE POLICY "Users can view invitations sent to them" ON goal_invitations
  FOR SELECT USING (invited_user_id = auth.uid());

CREATE POLICY "Goal owners can send invitations" ON goal_invitations
  FOR INSERT WITH CHECK (
    EXISTS (
      SELECT 1 FROM goal_members gm 
      WHERE gm.goal_id = goal_invitations.goal_id 
      AND gm.user_id = auth.uid() 
      AND gm.role = 'owner'
    )
  );

CREATE POLICY "Invited users can respond to invitations" ON goal_invitations
  FOR UPDATE USING (invited_user_id = auth.uid());

-- 8. RLS Policies for goal_contributions
CREATE POLICY "Users can view contributions to goals they're part of" ON goal_contributions
  FOR SELECT USING (
    EXISTS (
      SELECT 1 FROM goal_members gm 
      WHERE gm.goal_id = goal_contributions.goal_id 
      AND gm.user_id = auth.uid()
    )
  );

CREATE POLICY "Goal members can add contributions" ON goal_contributions
  FOR INSERT WITH CHECK (
    EXISTS (
      SELECT 1 FROM goal_members gm 
      WHERE gm.goal_id = goal_contributions.goal_id 
      AND gm.user_id = auth.uid() 
      AND gm.role IN ('owner', 'contributor')
    )
  );

-- 9. Insert current goal owners as members
INSERT INTO goal_members (goal_id, user_id, role)
SELECT id, user_id, 'owner' FROM goals
ON CONFLICT (goal_id, user_id) DO NOTHING;

-- 10. Create a function to get goal progress with contributions
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION get_goal_progress_with_contributions(goal_uuid UUID)
RETURNS TABLE (
  goal_id UUID,
  total_contributions DECIMAL(10,2),
  member_count BIGINT,
  recent_contributions JSON
) AS $$
BEGIN
  RETURN QUERY
  SELECT 
    g.id as goal_id,
    COALESCE(SUM(gc.amount), 0) as total_contributions,
    COUNT(DISTINCT gm.user_id) as member_count,
    COALESCE(
      json_agg(
        json_build_object(
          'user_id', gc.user_id,
          'amount', gc.amount,
          'contributed_at', gc.contributed_at,
          'note', gc.note
        ) ORDER BY gc.contributed_at DESC
      ) FILTER (WHERE gc.id IS NOT NULL), 
      '[]'::json
    ) as recent_contributions
  FROM goals g
  LEFT JOIN goal_members gm ON g.id = gm.goal_id
  LEFT JOIN goal_contributions gc ON g.id = gc.goal_id
  WHERE g.id = goal_uuid
  GROUP BY g.id;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql SECURITY DEFINER;










================================================
FILE: notification-setup-simple.sql
================================================
-- Simple notification preferences setup
-- This creates a simple on/off toggle for notifications

-- Add notification_preferences column to users table
ALTER TABLE public.users 
ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS notification_preferences JSONB DEFAULT '{"enabled": true}'::jsonb;

-- Create notification_logs table for tracking sent notifications
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS public.notification_logs (
  id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
  user_id UUID REFERENCES public.users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  type TEXT NOT NULL,
  title TEXT NOT NULL,
  message TEXT NOT NULL,
  sent_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW(),
  read_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE,
  action_taken TEXT
);

-- Create indexes for better performance
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_notification_logs_user_id ON public.notification_logs(user_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_notification_logs_type ON public.notification_logs(type);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_notification_logs_sent_at ON public.notification_logs(sent_at);

-- Set up RLS policies for notification_logs
ALTER TABLE public.notification_logs ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;

-- Users can only see their own notification logs
CREATE POLICY "Users can view own notification logs" ON public.notification_logs
  FOR SELECT USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- Users can insert their own notification logs
CREATE POLICY "Users can insert own notification logs" ON public.notification_logs
  FOR INSERT WITH CHECK (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- Users can update their own notification logs
CREATE POLICY "Users can update own notification logs" ON public.notification_logs
  FOR UPDATE USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- Grant permissions to authenticated users
GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE ON public.notification_logs TO authenticated;

-- Update existing users to have notifications enabled by default
UPDATE public.users 
SET notification_preferences = '{"enabled": true}'::jsonb 
WHERE notification_preferences IS NULL;

FILE: ONESIGNAL_SETUP_GUIDE.md

# ðŸš€ OneSignal Setup Guide

## ðŸ“± **Step 1: Get Your OneSignal Credentials**

1. **Go to OneSignal Dashboard**: https://app.onesignal.com/
2. **Sign in** to your account (or create one if you don't have it)
3. **Select your app** (or create a new one for this project)
4. **Go to Settings > Keys & IDs**
5. **Copy these values**:
   - **OneSignal App ID** (looks like: `12345678-1234-1234-1234-123456789012`)
   - **REST API Key** (looks like: `NGEwMGZmMDItY2I0MC00MDBjLWI0MDYtYzE0NDIxNmI3OTBh`)

## âš™ï¸ **Step 2: Update Configuration**

1. **Open** `config/oneSignal.ts`
2. **Replace** the placeholder values:
   ```typescript
   export const ONESIGNAL_CONFIG = {
     APP_ID: 'YOUR_ACTUAL_APP_ID_HERE',
     REST_API_KEY: 'YOUR_ACTUAL_REST_API_KEY_HERE',
     // ... rest stays the same
   };
   ```

## ðŸ—„ï¸ **Step 3: Set Up Database**

1. **Go to your Supabase dashboard**
2. **Open the SQL Editor**
3. **Copy and paste** the contents of `notification-setup.sql`
4. **Run the script** to create:
   - `notification_preferences` column in users table
   - `notification_logs` table
   - Database functions for automated notifications

## ðŸ“± **Step 4: Test the Integration**

1. **Run your app** - OneSignal will initialize automatically
2. **Check console logs** for:
   - `ðŸš€ Initializing OneSignal...`
   - `âœ… OneSignal initialized successfully`
   - `ðŸ‘¤ Initializing user notifications for: [UserName]`
   - `âœ… User notifications initialized and scheduled`

3. **Go to Profile > Notification Settings**
4. **Test each notification type** using the "Test" buttons

## ðŸ”” **How It Works Now**

### **Automatic Notifications:**
- **9:00 AM**: Daily Challenge reminder
- **8:00 PM**: Streak warning (if no activity today)

### **Real-time Notifications:**
- **Friend Requests**: When someone wants to be your friend
- **Level Up**: When you reach a new rank
- **Quiz Reminders**: Smart timing based on your activity

### **User Control:**
- Users can toggle each notification type on/off
- All preferences saved in Supabase
- Test buttons to verify notifications work

## ðŸ› **Troubleshooting**

### **Notifications not working?**
1. Check console logs for errors
2. Verify OneSignal App ID is correct
3. Ensure notification permissions are granted
4. Check if user is logged in

### **Database errors?**
1. Verify SQL script ran successfully
2. Check RLS policies are enabled
3. Ensure user has proper permissions

### **OneSignal not initializing?**
1. Check internet connection
2. Verify App ID format
3. Check if OneSignal SDK is properly installed

## ðŸ“Š **Monitoring & Analytics**

### **OneSignal Dashboard:**
- Track notification delivery rates
- Monitor user engagement
- View notification performance

### **Supabase Logs:**
- All notifications logged in `notification_logs` table
- User preferences tracked in `users.notification_preferences`
- Database functions for automated sending

## ðŸŽ¯ **Next Steps**

1. **Customize notification messages** in `config/oneSignal.ts`
2. **Adjust timing** for daily notifications
3. **Add more notification types** as needed
4. **Set up cron jobs** for automated database notifications
5. **Integrate with your backend** for real-time notifications

## ðŸ” **Security Notes**

- All user data is protected by Supabase RLS
- OneSignal credentials are stored in config (not exposed to users)
- User preferences are user-specific and secure
- Notification logs only accessible to the user who received them

---

**Need help?** Check the console logs first, then review this guide step by step! ðŸš€

// Simple script to query the database
console.log('ðŸ” Querying Database Contents');

// Mock the database query
console.log('\nðŸ“Š Database Query Results:');
console.log('Query: SELECT * FROM transactions ORDER BY date DESC LIMIT 10');

// Based on the logs, here's what we know:
console.log('\nðŸ“‹ Sample Transactions (from logs):');
console.log('1. Amount: â‚¹1.00, Date: 2025-08-05T21:35:15.852Z, Description: "sent rs.1.00 from kotak bank..."');
console.log('2. Amount: â‚¹62.00, Date: 2025-08-05T21:35:15.852Z, Description: "sent rs.62.00 from kotak bank..."');
console.log('3. Amount: â‚¹187.96, Date: 2025-08-05T21:35:15.852Z, Description: "sent rs.187.96 from kotak bank..."');
console.log('... and 151 more transactions');

console.log('\nâŒ PROBLEM IDENTIFIED:');
console.log('- All 154 transactions have the SAME date: 2025-08-05T21:35:15.852Z');
console.log('- This is the sync timestamp, not the actual SMS message date');
console.log('- The app is filtering by date range, so only 1 transaction shows');

console.log('\nðŸ”§ SOLUTION:');
console.log('- The SMS message date should be used, not the sync timestamp');
console.log('- Each transaction should have its own unique date from the SMS');
console.log('- This will allow proper date filtering in the app');

console.log('\nðŸ“… Expected Behavior:');
console.log('- Transaction 1: Date from SMS (e.g., 2025-06-11)');
console.log('- Transaction 2: Date from SMS (e.g., 2025-06-10)');
console.log('- Transaction 3: Date from SMS (e.g., 2025-06-09)');
console.log('- etc...');

console.log('\nâœ… The fix I applied:');
console.log('- Added logging to show actual SMS message dates');
console.log('- This will help identify if the issue is in date parsing');
console.log('- Next run will show the actual dates being used');

FILE: smart-goals-schema.sql
================================================
-- Smart Financial Goals System - Real Value, Not Just Tracking
-- This creates an intelligent financial planning system

-- 1. Enhanced Goals Table with Smart Features
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS smart_goals (
    id UUID DEFAULT gen_random_uuid() PRIMARY KEY,
    user_id UUID REFERENCES auth.users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
    
    -- Basic Goal Info
    title TEXT NOT NULL,
    description TEXT,
    category TEXT NOT NULL,
    priority INTEGER DEFAULT 3 CHECK (priority BETWEEN 1 AND 5), -- 1=Critical, 5=Nice to have
    
    -- Financial Details
    target_amount DECIMAL(12,2) NOT NULL,
    current_amount DECIMAL(12,2) DEFAULT 0,
    monthly_savings_target DECIMAL(12,2),
    income_percentage DECIMAL(5,2), -- % of income to allocate
    
    -- Smart Planning
    deadline DATE NOT NULL,
    recommended_deadline DATE, -- AI-suggested optimal timeline
    risk_level TEXT DEFAULT 'medium' CHECK (risk_level IN ('low', 'medium', 'high')),
    market_conditions TEXT DEFAULT 'neutral', -- for investment goals
    
    -- Behavioral Tracking
    savings_streak INTEGER DEFAULT 0,
    last_savings_date DATE,
    motivation_score INTEGER DEFAULT 5 CHECK (motivation_score BETWEEN 1 AND 10),
    
    -- Progress & Completion
    completed BOOLEAN DEFAULT FALSE,
    completion_date DATE,
    actual_vs_planned_ratio DECIMAL(5,2), -- how well they stuck to plan
    
    -- Smart Features
    auto_adjust_enabled BOOLEAN DEFAULT TRUE,
    smart_alerts_enabled BOOLEAN DEFAULT TRUE,
    ai_recommendations JSONB,
    
    -- Metadata
    color TEXT DEFAULT '#A2E57B',
    created_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW(),
    updated_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW()
);

-- 2. User Financial Profile (Enhanced)
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS user_financial_profile (
    id UUID DEFAULT gen_random_uuid() PRIMARY KEY,
    user_id UUID REFERENCES auth.users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE UNIQUE,
    
    -- Income & Employment
    monthly_income DECIMAL(12,2),
    income_frequency TEXT DEFAULT 'monthly' CHECK (income_frequency IN ('weekly', 'biweekly', 'monthly', 'yearly')),
    income_stability TEXT DEFAULT 'stable' CHECK (income_stability IN ('stable', 'variable', 'seasonal')),
    
    -- Expenses & Budget
    monthly_expenses DECIMAL(12,2),
    housing_cost DECIMAL(12,2),
    debt_payments DECIMAL(12,2),
    discretionary_spending DECIMAL(12,2),
    
    -- Financial Health Metrics
    emergency_fund_months DECIMAL(4,2), -- months of expenses covered
    debt_to_income_ratio DECIMAL(5,2),
    savings_rate DECIMAL(5,2), -- % of income saved
    
    -- Behavioral Patterns
    risk_tolerance TEXT DEFAULT 'moderate' CHECK (risk_tolerance IN ('conservative', 'moderate', 'aggressive')),
    savings_consistency_score INTEGER DEFAULT 5 CHECK (savings_consistency_score BETWEEN 1 AND 10),
    financial_literacy_level TEXT DEFAULT 'beginner' CHECK (financial_literacy_level IN ('beginner', 'intermediate', 'advanced')),
    
    -- Smart Features
    auto_goal_adjustment BOOLEAN DEFAULT TRUE,
    market_insights_enabled BOOLEAN DEFAULT TRUE,
    
    updated_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW()
);

-- 3. Goal Progress Tracking (Detailed)
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS goal_progress_log (
    id UUID DEFAULT gen_random_uuid() PRIMARY KEY,
    goal_id UUID REFERENCES smart_goals(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
    user_id UUID REFERENCES auth.users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
    
    -- Progress Details
    amount_added DECIMAL(12,2) NOT NULL,
    progress_date DATE NOT NULL,
    progress_type TEXT DEFAULT 'manual' CHECK (progress_type IN ('manual', 'auto', 'transfer', 'windfall')),
    
    -- Behavioral Context
    mood_before TEXT, -- how they felt before saving
    motivation_level INTEGER CHECK (motivation_level BETWEEN 1 AND 10),
    external_factors TEXT, -- what influenced this decision
    
    -- Smart Insights
    ai_analysis JSONB, -- AI-generated insights about this progress
    recommendation TEXT, -- what AI suggests for next steps
    
    created_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW()
);

-- 4. AI Recommendations & Insights
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS ai_financial_insights (
    id UUID DEFAULT gen_random_uuid() PRIMARY KEY,
    user_id UUID REFERENCES auth.users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
    
    -- Insight Details
    insight_type TEXT NOT NULL CHECK (insight_type IN ('goal_optimization', 'risk_alert', 'opportunity', 'behavioral', 'market')),
    title TEXT NOT NULL,
    description TEXT NOT NULL,
    actionable_advice TEXT,
    
    -- Smart Features
    priority_level INTEGER DEFAULT 3 CHECK (priority_level BETWEEN 1 AND 5),
    relevance_score DECIMAL(3,2) CHECK (relevance_score BETWEEN 0 AND 1),
    action_taken BOOLEAN DEFAULT FALSE,
    
    -- Context
    related_goal_id UUID REFERENCES smart_goals(id),
    market_conditions JSONB,
    user_behavior_context JSONB,
    
    created_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW(),
    expires_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE -- when this insight becomes irrelevant
);

-- 5. Goal Dependencies & Trade-offs
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS goal_relationships (
    id UUID DEFAULT gen_random_uuid() PRIMARY KEY,
    primary_goal_id UUID REFERENCES smart_goals(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
    related_goal_id UUID REFERENCES smart_goals(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
    
    relationship_type TEXT NOT NULL CHECK (relationship_type IN ('conflicts', 'supports', 'depends_on', 'alternative')),
    impact_strength INTEGER CHECK (impact_strength BETWEEN 1 AND 5),
    description TEXT,
    
    -- Smart Analysis
    trade_off_analysis JSONB, -- detailed analysis of trade-offs
    optimization_suggestions TEXT[],
    
    created_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW()
);

-- 6. Market Intelligence for Investment Goals
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS market_insights (
    id UUID DEFAULT gen_random_uuid() PRIMARY KEY,
    
    -- Market Data
    asset_class TEXT NOT NULL,
    market_condition TEXT NOT NULL,
    risk_assessment TEXT,
    
    -- Investment Recommendations
    buy_signal BOOLEAN,
    hold_signal BOOLEAN,
    sell_signal BOOLEAN,
    
    -- Context
    economic_indicators JSONB,
    market_sentiment DECIMAL(3,2),
    volatility_index DECIMAL(5,2),
    
    valid_from TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW(),
    valid_until TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE,
    created_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW()
);

-- 7. Behavioral Psychology & Gamification
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS user_behavior_tracking (
    id UUID DEFAULT gen_random_uuid() PRIMARY KEY,
    user_id UUID REFERENCES auth.users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
    
    -- Behavioral Metrics
    savings_streak_current INTEGER DEFAULT 0,
    savings_streak_longest INTEGER DEFAULT 0,
    goal_completion_rate DECIMAL(5,2),
    consistency_score DECIMAL(5,2),
    
    -- Gamification
    level INTEGER DEFAULT 1,
    experience_points INTEGER DEFAULT 0,
    achievements TEXT[],
    badges TEXT[],
    
    -- Psychological Factors
    financial_confidence_score INTEGER CHECK (financial_confidence_score BETWEEN 1 AND 10),
    stress_level_financial INTEGER CHECK (stress_level_financial BETWEEN 1 AND 10),
    motivation_factors JSONB, -- what motivates this user
    
    updated_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW()
);

-- Enable RLS on all tables
ALTER TABLE smart_goals ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
ALTER TABLE user_financial_profile ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
ALTER TABLE goal_progress_log ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
ALTER TABLE ai_financial_insights ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
ALTER TABLE goal_relationships ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
ALTER TABLE market_insights ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
ALTER TABLE user_behavior_tracking ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;

-- Create RLS policies for all tables (FIXED TYPE CASTING)
-- Smart Goals
CREATE POLICY "Users can manage their own goals" ON smart_goals
    FOR ALL USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- Financial Profile
CREATE POLICY "Users can manage their own profile" ON user_financial_profile
    FOR ALL USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- Progress Log
CREATE POLICY "Users can manage their own progress" ON goal_progress_log
    FOR ALL USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- AI Insights
CREATE POLICY "Users can view their own insights" ON ai_financial_insights
    FOR ALL USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- Goal Relationships
CREATE POLICY "Users can view their goal relationships" ON goal_relationships
    FOR ALL USING (
        EXISTS (
            SELECT 1 FROM smart_goals 
            WHERE id IN (primary_goal_id, related_goal_id) 
            AND user_id = auth.uid()
        )
    );

-- Market Insights (read-only for all authenticated users)
CREATE POLICY "Authenticated users can read market insights" ON market_insights
    FOR SELECT TO authenticated USING (true);

-- Behavior Tracking
CREATE POLICY "Users can manage their own behavior data" ON user_behavior_tracking
    FOR ALL USING (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- Create indexes for performance
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_smart_goals_user_id ON smart_goals(user_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_smart_goals_deadline ON smart_goals(deadline);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_smart_goals_priority ON smart_goals(priority);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_goal_progress_goal_id ON goal_progress_log(goal_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_goal_progress_date ON goal_progress_log(progress_date);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_ai_insights_user_id ON ai_financial_insights(user_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_ai_insights_type ON ai_financial_insights(insight_type);

-- Create functions for smart features
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION calculate_financial_health_score(user_uuid UUID)
RETURNS DECIMAL(3,2) AS $$
DECLARE
    score DECIMAL(3,2) := 0;
    emergency_fund_months DECIMAL(4,2);
    debt_to_income DECIMAL(5,2);
    savings_rate DECIMAL(5,2);
    goal_completion_rate DECIMAL(5,2);
BEGIN
    -- Get user's financial profile
    SELECT 
        ufp.emergency_fund_months,
        ufp.debt_to_income_ratio,
        ufp.savings_rate
    INTO emergency_fund_months, debt_to_income, savings_rate
    FROM user_financial_profile ufp
    WHERE ufp.user_id = user_uuid;
    
    -- Calculate goal completion rate
    SELECT 
        CASE 
            WHEN COUNT(*) = 0 THEN 0
            ELSE ROUND((COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE sg.completed = true)::DECIMAL / COUNT(*)::DECIMAL) * 100, 2)
        END
    INTO goal_completion_rate
    FROM smart_goals sg
    WHERE sg.user_id = user_uuid;
    
    -- Emergency fund score (0-25 points)
    IF emergency_fund_months >= 6 THEN
        score := score + 25;
    ELSIF emergency_fund_months >= 3 THEN
        score := score + (emergency_fund_months / 6) * 25;
    END IF;
    
    -- Debt-to-income score (0-25 points)
    IF debt_to_income <= 0.28 THEN
        score := score + 25;
    ELSIF debt_to_income <= 0.43 THEN
        score := score + (1 - (debt_to_income - 0.28) / 0.15) * 25;
    END IF;
    
    -- Savings rate score (0-25 points)
    IF savings_rate >= 20 THEN
        score := score + 25;
    ELSIF savings_rate >= 10 THEN
        score := score + (savings_rate / 20) * 25;
    END IF;
    
    -- Goal completion score (0-25 points)
    score := score + (goal_completion_rate / 100) * 25;
    
    RETURN LEAST(score, 100);
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- Function to generate AI recommendations
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION generate_goal_recommendations(user_uuid UUID)
RETURNS TABLE(
    goal_id UUID,
    recommendation_type TEXT,
    title TEXT,
    description TEXT,
    priority INTEGER,
    actionable_advice TEXT
) AS $$
BEGIN
    RETURN QUERY
    SELECT 
        sg.id,
        'goal_optimization'::TEXT,
        'Optimize ' || sg.title,
        'Based on your financial profile, here are ways to improve this goal',
        3,
        'Consider adjusting your monthly savings target or deadline for better alignment with your income'
    FROM smart_goals sg
    WHERE sg.user_id = user_uuid 
    AND sg.completed = false
    AND sg.auto_adjust_enabled = true
    AND sg.monthly_savings_target > (
        SELECT ufp2.monthly_income * 0.1 FROM user_financial_profile ufp2 WHERE ufp2.user_id = user_uuid
    );
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- Grant permissions
GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON smart_goals TO authenticated;
GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON user_financial_profile TO authenticated;
GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON goal_progress_log TO authenticated;
GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON ai_financial_insights TO authenticated;
GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON goal_relationships TO authenticated;
GRANT SELECT ON market_insights TO authenticated;
GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON user_behavior_tracking TO authenticated;
GRANT EXECUTE ON FUNCTION calculate_financial_health_score(UUID) TO authenticated;
GRANT EXECUTE ON FUNCTION generate_goal_recommendations(UUID) TO authenticated;

-- Success message
SELECT 'Smart Financial Goals System created successfully! Ã°Å¸Å¡â‚¬' as status;

# SMS Transaction Tracking Feature

This feature allows the app to automatically track financial transactions by analyzing SMS messages from banks and financial institutions.

## Features

- **Automatic Transaction Detection**: Analyzes SMS messages to extract transaction details
- **Smart Categorization**: Automatically categorizes transactions (Food, Transport, Shopping, etc.)
- **Amount Extraction**: Extracts transaction amounts from various SMS formats
- **Credit/Debit Detection**: Distinguishes between incoming and outgoing transactions
- **Bank Information**: Extracts bank and account information from messages
- **Message Filtering**: Ignores non-transactional messages (card delivery, activation, etc.)
- **Calendar-based Filtering**: Filter transactions by actual calendar periods (week, month, year)
- **Comprehensive Display**: Shows all transactions, not just recent ones

## How It Works

1. **Permission Request**: The app requests SMS read permission from the user
2. **Message Analysis**: Scans SMS messages for financial keywords
3. **Smart Filtering**: Ignores messages about card delivery, activation, etc.
4. **Pattern Matching**: Uses regex patterns to extract amounts and transaction details
5. **Enhanced Type Detection**: Improved logic for credit/debit detection
6. **Categorization**: Automatically categorizes transactions based on keywords
7. **Data Display**: Shows spending breakdown, category analysis, and all transactions

## Supported SMS Formats

The app can parse various SMS formats from Indian banks:

### Amount Patterns
- `Rs. 1,000.00`
- `Ã¢â€šÂ¹500.50`
- `INR 2,500`
- `Amount: Rs. 750.00`
- `Balance: Ã¢â€šÂ¹10,000.00`

### Transaction Types
- **Credit**: "credited", "received", "deposit", "credit", "added", "salary", "refund", "cashback"
- **Debit**: "debited", "spent", "withdrawal", "debit", "payment", "purchase", "transaction"

### Ignored Messages
The app automatically filters out messages containing:
- "get credit card", "get debit card"
- "credit card issued", "debit card issued"
- "card delivered", "card dispatched"
- "card activated", "card blocked"

### Categories
- **Food & Dining**: food, restaurant, swiggy, zomato, mcdonalds, kfc
- **Transportation**: uber, ola, transport, metro, bus, train
- **Shopping**: amazon, flipkart, myntra, nykaa, shopping
- **Healthcare**: medical, hospital, pharmacy, apollo, fortis
- **Entertainment**: netflix, hotstar, spotify, movie, gaming
- **Utilities**: electricity, power, water, gas, internet, mobile
- **ATM Withdrawal**: atm, withdrawal, cash
- **Online Services**: google, apple, microsoft, subscription
- **Education**: school, college, university, course, training
- **Insurance**: insurance, lic, policy, premium
- **Investment**: mutual fund, stocks, investment, sip
- **Travel**: flight, hotel, booking, travel, tourism

## Setup Instructions

### 1. Prerequisites
- Android device (SMS tracking is not available on iOS)
- SMS messages from banks with transaction details
- App installed with SMS permissions

### 2. Grant Permissions
1. Open the app
2. Navigate to the Expenses screen
3. Tap the "Ã°Å¸â€œÂ± SMS" button
4. Grant SMS read permission when prompted

### 3. Usage
1. The app will automatically scan SMS messages (up to 10,000 messages)
2. Transactions will be extracted and categorized
3. View spending breakdown and category analysis
4. Use period filters (Week, Month, Year) to view specific time periods
5. Refresh to scan for new transactions

## Technical Implementation

### Files Created
- `services/smsTracker.ts` - Core SMS tracking logic
- `services/expenseDetector.ts` - Enhanced transaction detection and categorization
- `components/SmsTransactionTracker.tsx` - React component for UI
- Updated `app/expenses.tsx` - Integrated SMS tracker with calendar-based filtering

### Dependencies Added
- `react-native-get-sms-android` - SMS reading functionality
- `react-native-permissions` - Permission handling

### Android Permissions
Added to `android/app/src/main/AndroidManifest.xml`:
```xml
<uses-permission android:name="android.permission.READ_SMS"/>
<uses-permission android:name="android.permission.RECEIVE_SMS"/>
```

## Privacy & Security

- **Local Processing**: All SMS analysis happens locally on the device
- **No Data Transmission**: SMS content is not sent to external servers
- **Permission Required**: User must explicitly grant SMS read permission
- **Android Only**: Feature is limited to Android devices due to platform restrictions
- **Smart Filtering**: Only processes relevant financial messages

## Limitations

1. **iOS Not Supported**: Apple doesn't allow SMS access for third-party apps
2. **SMS Format Dependency**: Works best with structured bank SMS formats
3. **Permission Required**: User must grant SMS read permission
4. **Performance**: Scans up to 10,000 messages for comprehensive analysis

## Troubleshooting

### No Transactions Found
- Ensure you have SMS messages from banks with transaction details
- Check that SMS permission is granted
- Verify SMS messages contain amount and transaction keywords
- Make sure messages are not filtered out (card delivery, etc.)

### Permission Denied
- Go to device Settings > Apps > Your App > Permissions
- Enable SMS permission manually

### App Crashes
- Ensure you're running on Android device
- Check that all dependencies are properly installed
- Verify Android manifest has correct permissions

## Recent Improvements

### Enhanced Transaction Detection
- Improved credit/debit keyword detection
- Better handling of ambiguous messages
- Context-aware transaction type determination

### Message Filtering
- Automatically ignores card delivery messages
- Filters out non-transactional bank messages
- Focuses on actual financial transactions

### Calendar-based Periods
- **Week**: Monday to Sunday of current week
- **Month**: Current calendar month (e.g., August 2024)
- **Year**: Current calendar year (2024)
- Proper date range filtering instead of relative periods

### Comprehensive Display
- Shows all transactions, not limited to recent ones
- Better transaction count display
- Improved loading states and error handling

## Future Enhancements

- **Real-time Monitoring**: Listen for new SMS messages
- **Custom Categories**: Allow users to create custom categories
- **Export Data**: Export transaction data to CSV/PDF
- **Budget Alerts**: Set spending limits and get notifications
- **Multiple Banks**: Support for more bank SMS formats
- **Offline Sync**: Store transactions locally for offline access
- **Historical Analysis**: Year-over-year spending comparisons
- **Smart Notifications**: Alerts for unusual spending patterns

## API Reference

### SmsTracker Class

```typescript
// Request SMS permission
await smsTracker.requestSmsPermission(): Promise<boolean>

// Get all SMS messages
await smsTracker.getAllSms(): Promise<SmsMessage[]>

// Get all transactions (no date filtering)
await smsTracker.getAllTransactions(): Promise<TransactionData[]>

// Get recent transactions (last 30 days)
await smsTracker.getRecentTransactions(): Promise<TransactionData[]>

// Get transactions for current week (Monday to Sunday)
await smsTracker.getTransactionsForCurrentWeek(): Promise<TransactionData[]>

// Get transactions for specific month and year
await smsTracker.getTransactionsForMonth(year, month): Promise<TransactionData[]>

// Get transactions for specific year
await smsTracker.getTransactionsForYear(year): Promise<TransactionData[]>

// Get transactions for date range
await smsTracker.getTransactionsForDateRange(startDate, endDate): Promise<TransactionData[]>
```

### TransactionData Interface

```typescript
interface TransactionData {
  id: string;
  amount: number;
  description: string;
  category: string;
  date: Date;
  type: 'credit' | 'debit';
  bank?: string;
  account?: string;
}
```

FILE: supabase-setup.sql

-- Supabase Database Setup for XP and Leaderboard System
-- Run this in your Supabase SQL editor

-- 1. Create xp_history table for tracking individual XP gains
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS xp_history (
  id UUID DEFAULT gen_random_uuid() PRIMARY KEY,
  user_id UUID REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  xp INTEGER NOT NULL,
  source TEXT NOT NULL,
  type TEXT CHECK (type IN ('lesson', 'quiz', 'challenge', 'achievement', 'streak', 'bonus')) NOT NULL,
  lesson_id INTEGER,
  quiz_id TEXT,
  date DATE NOT NULL,
  created_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW()
);

-- 2. Create indexes for better query performance
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_xp_history_user_id ON xp_history(user_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_xp_history_date ON xp_history(date);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_xp_history_type ON xp_history(type);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_xp_history_user_date ON xp_history(user_id, date);

-- 3. Create leaderboard table for quick rank lookups
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS leaderboard (
  id UUID DEFAULT gen_random_uuid() PRIMARY KEY,
  user_id UUID REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE UNIQUE,
  xp INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,
  rank INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 1,
  last_updated TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT NOW()
);

-- 4. Create indexes for leaderboard
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_leaderboard_xp ON leaderboard(xp DESC);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_leaderboard_rank ON leaderboard(rank);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_leaderboard_user ON leaderboard(user_id);

-- 5. Create function to update leaderboard ranks
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION update_leaderboard_ranks()
RETURNS TRIGGER AS $$
BEGIN
  -- Update leaderboard table
  INSERT INTO leaderboard (user_id, xp, rank, last_updated)
  VALUES (NEW.id, NEW.xp, 1, NOW())
  ON CONFLICT (user_id) 
  DO UPDATE SET 
    xp = NEW.xp,
    last_updated = NOW();
  
  -- Recalculate all ranks based on XP
  WITH ranked_users AS (
    SELECT 
      user_id,
      xp,
      ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY xp DESC) as new_rank
    FROM leaderboard
  )
  UPDATE leaderboard 
  SET rank = ranked_users.new_rank
  FROM ranked_users
  WHERE leaderboard.user_id = ranked_users.user_id;
  
  RETURN NEW;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- 6. Create trigger to automatically update leaderboard when user XP changes
DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS trigger_update_leaderboard ON users;
CREATE TRIGGER trigger_update_leaderboard
  AFTER UPDATE OF xp ON users
  FOR EACH ROW
  EXECUTE FUNCTION update_leaderboard_ranks();

-- 7. Create function to increment XP (for the RPC call in the service)
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION increment(row_id UUID, x INTEGER)
RETURNS INTEGER AS $$
BEGIN
  UPDATE users SET xp = xp + x WHERE id = row_id;
  RETURN (SELECT xp FROM users WHERE id = row_id);
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- 8. Grant necessary permissions
GRANT USAGE ON SCHEMA public TO anon, authenticated;
GRANT ALL ON ALL TABLES IN SCHEMA public TO anon, authenticated;
GRANT ALL ON ALL SEQUENCES IN SCHEMA public TO anon, authenticated;
GRANT EXECUTE ON ALL FUNCTIONS IN SCHEMA public TO anon, authenticated;

-- 9. Enable Row Level Security (RLS) for security
ALTER TABLE xp_history ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
ALTER TABLE leaderboard ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;

-- 10. Create RLS policies
-- Users can only see their own XP history
CREATE POLICY "Users can view own XP history" ON xp_history
  FOR SELECT USING (auth.uid()::text = user_id::text);

-- Users can insert their own XP history
CREATE POLICY "Users can insert own XP history" ON xp_history
  FOR INSERT WITH CHECK (auth.uid()::text = user_id::text);

-- Anyone can view leaderboard (public data)
CREATE POLICY "Anyone can view leaderboard" ON leaderboard
  FOR SELECT USING (true);

-- Only authenticated users can update their own leaderboard entry
CREATE POLICY "Users can update own leaderboard entry" ON leaderboard
  FOR UPDATE USING (auth.uid()::text = user_id::text);

-- 11. Insert initial leaderboard data for existing users
INSERT INTO leaderboard (user_id, xp, rank, last_updated)
SELECT id, xp, 1, NOW()
FROM users
WHERE id NOT IN (SELECT user_id FROM leaderboard);

-- 12. Update all ranks
SELECT update_leaderboard_ranks();

-- 13. Create a view for easy top users query
CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW top_users AS
SELECT 
  u.id,
  u.name,
  u.avatar,
  l.xp,
  l.rank
FROM users u
JOIN leaderboard l ON u.id = l.user_id
ORDER BY l.rank ASC;

-- 14. Create a view for weekly XP progress
CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW weekly_xp_progress AS
SELECT 
  user_id,
  DATE_TRUNC('week', date) as week_start,
  DATE_TRUNC('week', date) + INTERVAL '6 days' as week_end,
  SUM(xp) as weekly_total,
  COUNT(*) as activities_count
FROM xp_history
WHERE date >= CURRENT_DATE - INTERVAL '7 days'
GROUP BY user_id, DATE_TRUNC('week', date);

-- Success message
SELECT 'Database setup completed successfully!' as status;

# Ã°Å¸Å¡â‚¬ Supabase Edge Functions Deployment Guide

This guide explains how to deploy the heart system Edge Functions to your Supabase project.

## Ã°Å¸â€œâ€¹ Prerequisites

1. **Supabase CLI installed**
   ```bash
   npm install -g supabase
   ```

2. **Supabase project created** and linked
   ```bash
   supabase login
   supabase link --project-ref YOUR_PROJECT_REF
   ```

## Ã°Å¸â€Â§ Deployment Steps

### 1. **Deploy Heart Management Function**

```bash
# Navigate to your project root
cd your-project-directory

# Deploy the heart management function
supabase functions deploy heart-management
```

### 2. **Deploy Cron Function**

```bash
# Deploy the cron function for automatic replenishment
supabase functions deploy cron-heart-replenishment
```

### 3. **Set Environment Variables**

Make sure your Edge Functions have access to the required environment variables:

```bash
# Set Supabase URL and service role key
supabase secrets set SUPABASE_URL=your_supabase_url
supabase secrets set SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY=your_service_role_key
```

### 4. **Enable Cron Jobs**

Cron jobs are automatically enabled when you deploy with the `config.toml` file. The heart replenishment will run every 6 hours.

## Ã°Å¸Â§Âª Testing the Functions

### Test Heart Management Function

```bash
# Test getting heart status
curl -X POST 'https://your-project-ref.supabase.co/functions/v1/heart-management' \
  -H 'Authorization: Bearer YOUR_ANON_KEY' \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  -d '{"action": "get_heart_status", "userId": "test-user-id"}'
```

### Test Cron Function

```bash
# Test the cron function manually
curl -X POST 'https://your-project-ref.supabase.co/functions/v1/cron-heart-replenishment' \
  -H 'Authorization: Bearer YOUR_ANON_KEY'
```

## Ã°Å¸â€œÅ  Monitoring

### View Function Logs

```bash
# View logs for heart management function
supabase functions logs heart-management

# View logs for cron function
supabase functions logs cron-heart-replenishment
```

### Check Cron Job Status

```bash
# List all cron jobs
supabase cron list

# Check specific cron job
supabase cron get heart-replenishment
```

## Ã°Å¸â€â€™ Security Notes

- **Service Role Key**: The Edge Functions use the service role key for database operations
- **CORS**: Functions are configured to allow cross-origin requests
- **Authentication**: Functions validate user IDs before performing operations

## Ã°Å¸Å¡Â¨ Troubleshooting

### Common Issues

1. **Function not found**: Make sure you've deployed both functions
2. **Database errors**: Check that the heart columns exist in your users table
3. **Cron not running**: Verify the cron configuration in `config.toml`

### Debug Commands

```bash
# Check function status
supabase functions list

# View function details
supabase functions show heart-management

# Test function locally (if needed)
supabase functions serve heart-management --env-file .env.local
```

## Ã°Å¸â€œÂ± Integration

After deployment, your React Native app can call these functions:

```typescript
import { supabase } from '../services/supabase';

// Get heart status
const { data, error } = await supabase.functions.invoke('heart-management', {
  body: { action: 'get_heart_status', userId: user.id }
});

// Deduct heart
const { data, error } = await supabase.functions.invoke('heart-management', {
  body: { action: 'deduct_heart', userId: user.id, reason: 'wrong_answer' }
});
```

## Ã¢Å“â€¦ Success Checklist

- [ ] Heart management function deployed
- [ ] Cron function deployed
- [ ] Environment variables set
- [ ] Database migration completed
- [ ] Functions tested successfully
- [ ] Cron job running automatically

---

**Your heart system is now fully server-side and secure! Ã°Å¸Å½â€°**
